loria Anzaldúa in 1983, and visual art produced during the same period by Betye Saar, Ana Mendieta, Yolanda López, and others, curated by their contemporary, artist Celia Herrera Rodríguez. Bridge continues to reflect an evolving definition of feminism, one that can effectively adapt to and help inform an understanding of the changing economic and social conditions of women of color in the United States and throughout the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexMinority authors. 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authors. 0aFeminismvLiterary collections. 0aMinority womenvLiterary collections. 0aRadicalismvLiterary collections. 0aWomenzUnited StatesvLiterary collections. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : Asian American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aAlarcón, Norma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnzaldúa, Gloria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnzaldúa, Gloria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBambara, Toni Cade, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanaan, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrillo, Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Cheryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniels, Gabrielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLim, Genny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/